iv1_text: Well, this would be an experience that convinced me that I was NOT spiritual.  My mother was dying, and she was all tangled up in trying to 'get right with God', and trying to have all her spiritual ducks in a row, so to speak.  And I realized that if God would care if a dying woman had gotten everything 'right', if he would turn her away from heaven if she hadn't 'checked all the boxes', then that was a god that I wanted NO part of.  And so I began thinking.  And I thought - every people group in the world, for all of human history, has usually had some belief system - some deity or other.  What makes this ONE belief system, this ONE god (christianity, jesus, etc) the RIGHT one?  Doesn't it make more sense that ALL of them are wrong?  I mean - how arrogant.  And then I considered how so many of the religious stories and beliefs are based on earlier stories and beliefs from other people groups, and I realized....humans tell stories.  That's what makes us human.  But it doesn't make the stories we tell *factual*.  So - there is no God.  There is no reason other than tribalism to go killing each other around the globe for this shit.  And shouldn't we have evolved past blind tribalism by now?  I'm doing my part to evolve, by flushing religion and religious beliefs.  And that's how I became convinced of what I believe.

iv1_text: I do not have any religious beliefs.  I am strictly agnostic.  I am not a theist.  I am not an atheist.  There was not one experience that lead to this.  It was a journey that began when I was young.  I could not find a way to reconcile the existence of a God that is all good, all knowing, and all powerful, in a universe that includes so much suffering.  How can God be good and allow suffering to exist?  How can God allow suffering to exist when he can stop it?  Perhaps God is not good.  Perhaps God is not all powerful.  Perhaps God wants to stop suffering but can't.  Perhaps God is not god.  Because of this I would have considered my self an aetheist for a time. But I fell out with that, too.  There is no evidence one way or the other.  God's existence cannot be proven.  God's non-existence cannot be proven either.  Perhaps it doesn't matter.  Perhaps God is irrelevant.  Perhaps there is nothing to be gained from claiming to have the answer to a question that no human being can answer.  Instead, I focus on internal questions.  I ask, "Who am I?"  I ask, "Why am I suffering?"  I ask, "Why is everone I know also

The room has to be clean, the clothes have to be clean, and you yourself have to be clean. We must use water to clean ourselves thoroughly after using the restroom, we should smell nice and brush our teeth often, and usually before every prayer I perform a purifying ritual called "wudu." I wash my hands, arms, mouth, nose, face, head, ears, and feet. I think, aside from the spiritual benefits, this prayer schedule has a lot of practical benefits for me as well throughout my day.

iv1_text: A typical day for me consists of getting about around 6:15. I feel a sense of peace, as it is still quiet and calm outside.  This experience doesn't last long, however, as by the time I arrive at work, usually around 7:15 - 7:20, rush hour is in full swing, and I prepare myself for the regular hustle and bustle of the day.  I mostly write code for a living - "computer programmer" would be an easier way to describe this to someone who doesn't know what 'code' is.  My job is to automate common tasks that my team members perform routinely, in order to find and gain efficiencies in our daily work.  This is the part of the job I enjoy the most.  I love automating routine, mind-numbing, boring tasks so that the machines do it, freeing up the humans to do more complex, thought-provoking work.

He advised that I take some time to myself and pray about everything that was going on.  So I did and I prayed every night until one night I went out and met up with new friends who I met through the church.  Among my prayers were to help me find a partner whom may be able to be there for me in my time of need.  Well turns out she was in that group of new friends.  She knew exactly how to comfort me.  She was like a gift from God.  It was then I regained much of my faith in my religious beliefs.  I decided to go with it and see if this young woman would want to go out with myself and she agreed. iv1_text: On Wednesdays, I make my weekly trip to the Comic Book Store.  I have been a reader and collector since I was 9 years old.  I'd place it centrally as a reason I love storytelling so much, and have made it my life's pursuit, in one form or another.  The partnership of image and word, thought and execution was made so clear to me at such a young age.  Anyway, that is why, every Wednesday, with what little disposable income I can muster I make the trip.  I have several titles I am a dedicated reader of, and am always searching for the next thing, the title, the idea that fills a void I didn't know I had, but simultaneously diagnoses and prescribes cure in one awesome blow.  it sometimes feels strange to have such a mid-century, real world hobby, and I think that may be why I still rededicate myself to it each week, even as time and money and storage space compete to make it untenable.  Whatever.  I am what I am, and come hell or next Wednesday, I'll be there.
purpose_guess: The religious stuff.

iv1_text: An everyday experience I have is a 5 kilometer run every morning. I wake up, drink two glasses of water, get dressed, brush my teeth, and go out for a run. It is a short run on a good day and longer on a less good day. I love running and it helps me to keep my energy up all day, starts me off on the right foot (so to speak), and clears my head, allowing me to focus entirely on my goals for the rest of the day. Following this run, I go inside to make a pot of coffee and write out my goals for the day that I want to accomplish while negotiating and calculating the abilities of these goals to assist me with my long-term goals. Sometimes, I lift weights following this. Usually it's just the run. I couldn't do without it. If I ever skip a morning run, which is extremely rare, I feel terrible throughout the day. My energy is low, my opinion of myself is extremely negative, and I usually shame-spiral into making bad eating and further workout decisions.
purpose_guess: I think that this study was looking to equate religious beliefs with the rhetoric of their story-writing.
